<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">


<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><img width="232" height="43" src="g198181bci001.gif" alt="GRAPHIC"></font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">One AAR
Place<br>
1100 N. Wood Dale Road<br>
Wood Dale, IL 60191</font></p>

<div style="margin:0pt 0pt 18.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><hr size="1" width="160" noshade color="black" align="left" style="width:120.0pt;"></div>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTICE OF ANNUAL MEETING OF
STOCKHOLDERS<br>
TO BE HELD ON WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 17, 2007</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Annual Meeting of
Stockholders of AAR CORP. for the year 2007 will be held at AAR CORP.&#146;s
headquarters, One AAR Place, 1100 North Wood Dale Road, Wood Dale, Illinois, on
Wednesday, October&nbsp;17, 2007, at 9:00&nbsp;A.M. (Chicago time). At the
meeting, stockholders will be asked to:</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 20.0pt;text-indent:-20.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">1.</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Elect four Class&nbsp;II
directors to serve until the 2010 Annual Meeting of Stockholders;</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 20.0pt;text-indent:-20.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">2.</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Ratify the
appointment of KPMG LLP as the Company&#146;s independent registered public
accounting firm for the fiscal year ending May&nbsp;31, 2008;</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt 20.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-20.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">3.</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Transact
any other business that may properly come before the 2007 Annual Meeting or any
adjournment(s)&nbsp;or postponement(s)&nbsp;of the meeting.</p>

<div align="center">

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse;">

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">August&nbsp;31, 2007</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">YOUR VOTE IS IMPORTANT</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">PLEASE DATE AND SIGN THE ENCLOSED
PROXY AND RETURN IT IN THE ENCLOSED STAMPED, ADDRESSED ENVELOPE, OR SUBMIT YOUR
PROXY BY TELEPHONE OR THE INTERNET SO THAT IF YOU ARE UNABLE TO ATTEND THE
MEETING, YOUR SHARES MAY NEVERTHELESS BE VOTED. NO POSTAGE IS REQUIRED FOR
MAILING IN THE UNITED STATES.</font></b></p>

  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:2.74%;">
  <p style="margin:6.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">42</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="0%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:.92%;">
  <p style="margin:6.0pt 0pt .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:2.64%;">

  2&nbsp;&#151; RATIFICATION OF APPOINTMENT OF KPMG LLP AS THE COMPANY&#146;S INDEPENDENT

 <p style="margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">ii</font></p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
<div>


<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><img width="232" height="43" src="g198181dei001.gif" alt="GRAPHIC"></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">One AAR
Place<br>
1100 N. Wood Dale Road<br>
Wood Dale, Illinois 60191</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">PROXY
STATEMENT</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">ANNUAL
MEETING OF STOCKHOLDERS<br>
October&nbsp;17, 2007</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><b><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">I. VOTING
INFORMATION<a name="I_VotingInformation_223538"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">This
Proxy Statement and the enclosed proxy card were mailed to stockholders on or
about August&nbsp;31, 2007, in connection with the solicitation of proxies by
the Board of Directors of the Company to be used at the 2007 Annual Meeting (&#147;Annual
Meeting&#148;).</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Who is entitled to
vote?<a name="WhoIsEntitledToVote_223549"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">If you were a stockholder of
record (i.e., you hold your shares in your own name rather than through a
broker, bank or other nominee) on August&nbsp;20, 2007, the Company&#146;s record
date, you may vote your shares at the Annual Meeting. If you were a street-name stockholder (i.e., you hold your shares through
a broker, bank or other nominee) on that date, you are considered a &#147;beneficial
owner&#148; of the stock. To vote those shares at the Annual Meeting, you must give
voting instructions to your broker, bank or other intermediary who is the &#147;nominee
holder&#148; of your shares. The Company has directed brokers, banks and other
nominee holders to obtain voting instructions from their beneficial owners. Proxies
submitted by nominee holders on behalf of beneficial owners will count toward a
quorum and will be voted as instructed by the nominee holder. You will receive
additional instructions from your broker, bank or other nominee explaining how
you may vote your shares held in street name. A list of registered stockholders
entitled to vote will be available at the Company&#146;s offices, 1100&nbsp;N.&nbsp;Wood
Dale Road, Wood Dale, Illinois, for 10 days prior to the meeting and at the
meeting location during the meeting.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">How do stockholders
vote by proxy or in person?<a name="HowDoStockholdersVoteByProxyOrInP_223605"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">If you owned common stock of
the Company (&#147;Common Stock&#148;) outstanding at the close of business on the record
date, August&nbsp;20, 2007, you may vote at the Annual Meeting by completing,
signing, dating and returning your proxy card in the postage-paid, addressed
envelope provided, or you may vote in person at the Annual Meeting. On that
date, 37,882,324&nbsp;shares of Common Stock were outstanding. You will have
one vote on each matter to be voted on for each share you owned on the record
date.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">How do stockholders
vote by telephone or through the internet?<a name="HowDoStockholdersVoteByTelephoneO_223629"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">You are encouraged to
vote either by telephone or through the internet. This will eliminate the need
to sign, date and return your proxy card. You can vote by telephone or through
the internet 24 hours a day, seven days a week, until 1:00&nbsp;a.m. (central
time) until the day of the Annual Meeting. If you vote by telephone or through
the internet, please do not return your proxy card.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#183;</font></b><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>To vote by telephone:</b></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 50.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Wingdings" style="font-size:8.0pt;">&#216;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><b>using a touch-tone phone, call 1-800-652-VOTE (8683)
toll-free, enter the control number imprinted on your proxy card, and follow
the voice prompts</b></p>


 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;line-height:10.0pt;margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">1</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='1',FILE='C:\fc\234162754872_D11055_2368866\19818-1-de.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 22 16:28 2007' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">



<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><b>To vote through the internet:</b></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt 50.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Wingdings" style="font-size:8.0pt;">&#216;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">Log
onto the internet website at </font>http://www.investorvote.com/expressvote and enter your voter control number imprinted on
your proxy card and mark the appropriate boxes to enter voting instructions</b></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">How
does a stockholder revoke a proxy?<a name="HowDoesAStockholderRevokeAProxy_223732"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">You may
revoke your vote at any time before your proxy is exercised, but only by (i)&nbsp;voting
in person at the Annual Meeting, (ii)&nbsp;submitting another proxy by
telephone or through the internet, or (iii)&nbsp;delivering a later dated,
signed proxy to the Secretary of the Company.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">How will proxy holders
vote shares?<a name="HowWillProxyHoldersVoteShares_223733"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Proxies will be voted in
accordance with instructions on the proxy. If no instructions are specified,
the proxy will be voted <b>FOR</b> the
election of the nominees for Class&nbsp;II director designated by the Board, <b>FOR</b> the ratification of the appointment of KPMG LLP as the
Company&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm, and upon any other
matter that may properly come before the Annual Meeting in the discretion and
best judgment of the named proxy holders. If any director nominee becomes
unavailable for election for any reason prior to the Annual Meeting vote, the
Board may reduce the number of directors to be elected or substitute another
person as nominee, and the named proxy holders will vote for the substitute
nominee.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">How will votes be
counted?<a name="HowWillVotesBeCounted_223734"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">All
votes cast in person or by proxy will be tabulated by the inspectors of
election appointed for the Annual Meeting. </font>A majority of the outstanding
shares of Common Stock entitled to vote, present in person or represented by
proxy at the Annual Meeting, will constitute a quorum. The inspectors of election will treat directions to withhold authority,
abstentions and broker non-votes (i.e., where a nominee holding shares for a
beneficial owner has not received voting instructions from the beneficial owner
with respect to a particular matter and such nominee does not possess or choose
to exercise his discretionary authority with respect to such matter) as shares
that are present for purposes of determining a quorum. Directions to withhold
authority will have no effect on the election of directors, because directors
are elected by a plurality of votes cast. Abstentions and broker non-votes will
be disregarded for purposes of determining whether a matter has been approved,
because they are not considered votes cast. It is not anticipated that there
will be any broker non-votes on the election of directors or the ratification
of the appointment of KPMG LLP since brokers will have discretion to vote on
these proposals.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Who is the Company&#146;s
proxy solicitor?<a name="WhoIsTheCompanysProxySolicitor_223735"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company has engaged D. F.
King&nbsp;&amp; Co., 48 Wall Street, New York, New York, to assist the Company
in soliciting proxies at a total estimated cost of $10,000, plus reasonable
out-of-pocket expenses. The cost of soliciting proxies will be paid by the
Company. D. F. King&nbsp;&amp; Co. may solicit proxies by mail, telephone,
facsimile, e-mail, or in person. Certain officers, directors and employees of
the Company may also solicit proxies.</font></p>


 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;line-height:10.0pt;margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">2</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">



<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><b><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">II. CORPORATE GOVERNANCE
INFORMATION<a name="Ii_CorporateGovernanceInformation_041740"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">General<a name="General_223842"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company has an ongoing commitment to good governance and business
practices. We regularly review our policies and procedures, giving due
consideration to current developments and &#147;best practices&#148; in the area of
corporate governance. We comply with all applicable Securities and Exchange
Commission (&#147;SEC&#148;) rules&nbsp;and regulations and New York Stock Exchange (&#147;NYSE&#148;)
listing rules&nbsp;and have adopted additional corporate governance practices
that we believe are in the best interests of the Company and its stockholders.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Copies of the following corporate governance
documents are available on the Company&#146;s web site (www.aarcorp.com/investorrelations/corporategovernance):</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Corporate Governance Guidelines</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Categorical Standards and Policy for Determining Director Independence</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Director Nominating Process and Selection Guidelines</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Code of Business Ethics and Conduct</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Audit Committee Charter</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Compensation Committee Charter</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Nominating and Governance Committee Charter</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Executive Committee Charter</p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">All these corporate governance
documents are also available in print to any stockholder upon written request
to the Secretary of the Company at the Company&#146;s address listed on the first page
of this Proxy Statement. The Company&#146;s Code of Business Ethics and Conduct
adopted by the Board of Directors applies to all employees, officers and
directors of the Company, including the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer,
the President and Chief Operating Officer, the Chief Financial Officer and the
Chief Accounting Officer and Controller. Employees are encouraged to report to
the Company any conduct that they believe in good faith to be in violation of
the Code of Business Ethics and Conduct. Amendments to the Code of Business
Ethics and Conduct and any waivers from the Code granted by the Board to
directors or executive officers will be filed with the SEC in accordance with
applicable rules&nbsp;and regulations and posted on the Company&#146;s web site
under the corporate governance link cited above.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company maintains an Ethics
Assist Line through a third-party provider to receive confidential complaints,
information, suggestions or recommendations, anonymously or otherwise,
concerning the Company, its officers, directors and employees, policies,
procedures, employment and business practices, accounting or audit matters,
financial reporting or compliance with other Company policies or applicable
regulatory or legal requirements. The Ethics Assist Line is toll-free and
permits callers, at their election, to identify themselves or remain anonymous.
The Ethics Assist Line can be accessed by dialing 1-800-418-6423
(x227) or via e-mail to confide2sv@securityvoice.com.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Information
concerning insider transactions in the Company&#146;s securities (SEC Section&nbsp;16(a)
Forms 3, 4 and 5) is also available on the Company&#146;s web site
(www.aarcorp.com/investor relations/insider trading).</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Information
concerning the structure, composition and independence of the Board of
Directors and Committees of the Board of Directors, as well as information
regarding director nomination and recommendation procedures, is provided in Section&nbsp;IV,
&#147;Board of Directors,&#148; on page&nbsp;7.</font></p>


 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;line-height:10.0pt;margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">3</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='3',FILE='C:\fc\234162754872_D11055_2368866\19818-1-de.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 22 16:28 2007' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">



<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Related-Party Transactions<a name="RelatedpartyTransactions_224004"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Nominating and Governance
Committee reviews, and makes recommendations to the Board of Directors with
respect to, all related-party transactions and relationships involving a
director or executive officer and the Company. The Company has no separate
related-party transaction policy; rather, various policy and procedures,
including the Company&#146;s Code of Business Ethics and Conduct and the annul
directors&#146; and officers&#146; questionnaires, require disclosure of transactions or
relationships that may constitute conflicts of interest or require disclosure
or affect an independence determination under the applicable SEC rules. Upon
learning of a transaction or a relationship that may constitute a conflict of
interest, require disclosure or cause a director not to be treated as
independent, the Nominating and Governance Committee determines if further
investigation is required and, if so, whether it should be conducted by the
Company&#146;s legal, internal audit, or other staff, or by outside advisors. The
Nominating and Governance Committee reviews the related-party transaction or
relationship, including the results of any investigation, and makes a
recommendation to the Board of Directors whether to approve or reject the
transaction or relationship. The Board of Directors then considers the matter
and makes its decision. Transactions and relationships that are determined to
be directly or indirectly material to the Company or a related person are
disclosed in the Company&#146;s Proxy Statement.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Mr.&nbsp;Ira A. Eichner, a former
director and Founder and Chairman of the Board of the Company, who retired from
the Board on October&nbsp;19, 2005, provides consulting services to the Company
pursuant to a consulting agreement that expires on October&nbsp;18, 2010, under
which he receives a quarterly consulting fee in the amount of $37,500. During
Fiscal 2007, Mr.&nbsp;Eichner received $150,000 in consulting fees. Mr.&nbsp;Eichner
is Founder and Chairman of the Board Emeritus, an honorary position, and Mr.&nbsp;Storch&#146;s
father-in-law.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Director
nominee Norman R. Bobins is the Chairman of the Board and a former President
and Chief Executive Officer of LaSalle Bank Corporation (&#147;LaSalle Bank&#148;) and
former Senior Executive Vice President of ABN AMRO Bank N.V., the Dutch parent
of LaSalle Bank. Since August, 2006, the Company has been party to a
$140,000,000 unsecured revolving credit facility with LaSalle Bank National
Association, an affiliate of LaSalle Bank, and various other Lenders. LaSalle
Bank&#146;s participation under the facility is $40,000,000. Under certain
circumstances the revolving credit commitment can be increased up to a maximum
of $175,000,000. The credit facility expires on August&nbsp;31, 2010 and
borrowings bear interest at LIBOR plus 125 to 200 basis points depending on
specified financial measurements. The credit facility also includes a non-use
fee which is currently 30 basis points on the unused portion of the facility.
The facility was made in the ordinary course of business and on substantially
the same terms, including interest rates and collateral, as those prevailing at
the time for comparable loans. There were no borrowings outstanding under this
facility during Fiscal 2007 and no interest was paid. The Company paid
approximately $600,000 in fees and non-use charges under the facility during Fiscal
2007.</font></p>


 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;line-height:10.0pt;margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">4</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><b><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">III.
SECURITY OWNERSHIP OF MANAGEMENT AND OTHERS<a name="Iii_SecurityOwnershipOfManagement_041806"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following tables show the
shares of Common Stock beneficially owned, as of July&nbsp;31, 2007, by
(i)&nbsp;each current director and nominee for election to the Board,
(ii)&nbsp;each executive officer named in the Summary Compensation Table,
(iii)&nbsp;all directors and executive officers of the Company as a group, and
(iv)&nbsp;each beneficial owner of more than 5% of the outstanding shares of
Common Stock. Except as noted, the nature of beneficial ownership for shares
shown in the tables is sole voting and investment power, and none of the shares
shown in the tables are pledged by any of the persons listed.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Security

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">1</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Includes
the following shares of the identified person that may be acquired within sixty
days of July&nbsp;31, 2007 through the exercise of stock options:&#160; Mr.&nbsp;Brocksmith, 17,000 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Clark,
98,094 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Fogleman, 17,000 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Goodwin, 17,000
shares; Mr.&nbsp;Pulsifer, 113,678 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko, 146,868 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Storch,
881,183 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Walfish, 17,000 shares; and Mr.&nbsp;Woodard, 3,500
shares; and all directors and executive officers as a group, 2,439,145 shares.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">2</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Includes
8,000 shares beneficially owned through KMK&nbsp;&amp; Associates, LLC in which
Mr.&nbsp;Kelly is a one-third owner.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">3</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Includes
3,700 shares beneficially owned by Mr.&nbsp;McDonald&#146;s dependent children, as
to which Mr.&nbsp;McDonald disclaims beneficial ownership.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">4</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Includes 26,224 shares beneficially owned by Mr.&nbsp;Storch&#146;s
wife (18,810 shares) and minor children (7,414 shares), as to which Mr.&nbsp;Storch
disclaims beneficial ownership.</font></p>

 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;line-height:10.0pt;margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">6</font></p>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='6',FILE='C:\fc\229162521110_H11179_2359436\19818-1-dg.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 17 16:25 2007' -->



<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
<div>


<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt .5pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Section&nbsp;16(a) Beneficial Ownership Reporting
Compliance<a name="Section16abeneficialOwnershipRepo_230839"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Based
solely upon a review of SEC Forms 3, 4 and 5 and upon related written
representations furnished to the Company with respect to its most recent fiscal
year, the Company believes that each person who, at any time during the fiscal
year, was a director or officer filed on a timely basis all reports required by
Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended, during
the most recent fiscal year, except that Mr.&nbsp;McDonald filed a late Form&nbsp;4
reporting a stock option exercise of 64,140 shares and the sale of 37,780
shares used to pay the related option exercise price and withholding taxes.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><b><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">IV. BOARD OF DIRECTORS<a name="Iv_BoardOfDirectors_230840"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Restated Certificate of Incorporation and By-Laws of the Company provide that
the Board shall consist of between three and fifteen directors, with the exact
number of directors to be set from time to time by the Board. The number of
directors is presently set at eleven with one vacancy for which the Board of
Directors has proposed and recommends a nominee to be elected by Stockholders
at the October Annual meeting. The members of the Board are divided into three
classes: Class&nbsp;I (three directors), Class&nbsp;II (four directors) and Class&nbsp;III
(four directors). One class is elected each year for a three-year term.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During
the fiscal year beginning June&nbsp;1, 2006 and ending May&nbsp;31, 2007 (&#147;Fiscal
2007&#148;), the Board held five meetings. Seven incumbent directors attended 100%
of the aggregate meetings of the Board and the committees on which they served
during Fiscal 2007; due to medical reasons, Mr.&nbsp;Boyce and Mr.&nbsp;Walfish
attended less than 75% of the aggregate meetings of the Board and the
committees on which they served. All the members of the Company&#146;s Board of
Directors attended the Company&#146;s 2006 Annual Meeting of Stockholders.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt .5pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Director Independence<a name="DirectorIndependence_230840"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">A
majority of the members of the Board of Directors must be independent directors
under the criteria established by the Board and under applicable NYSE rules. The
Nominating and Governance Committee and the Board of Directors review each
director annually and make a determination concerning independence after
consideration of all known facts and circumstances. The Board has established
categorical standards to assist it in determining director independence. The
Company&#146;s &#147;Categorical Standards and Policy for Determining Director
Independence&#148; include all of the elements of the applicable SEC and NYSE rules&nbsp;with
respect to director independence, as well as those of the Company, and are
attached as Appendix 1 to this Proxy Statement. Based on these categorical
standards and its review of all relevant facts and information available and
the recommendations of the Nominating and Governance Committee, the Board, at
its meeting in July 2007, affirmatively determined that no director has a
material relationship with the Company that would impair the director&#146;s ability
to exercise independent judgment and, accordingly, each director is an
independent director, except for David P. Storch, due to his status as Chairman
of the Board and Chief Executive Officer of the Company, and Timothy J.
Romenesko, due to his status as President and Chief Operating Officer of the
Company. Under the NYSE rules, a director employed by the Company is not an
independent director by definition.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Board of Directors also affirmatively determined that director nominee Norman
R. Bobins is independent. Mr. Bobins is the Chairman of the Board and former President
and Chief Executive Officer of LaSalle Bank and former Executive Senior Vice President
of ABN AMRO Bank N.V., the Dutch parent of LaSalle Bank. The Company has an
unsecured revolving credit facility with LaSalle Bank National Association, an
affiliate of LaSalle Bank. See &#147;Corporate Governance Information&nbsp;&#151; Related-Party
Transactions&#148; for additional information regarding this transaction. The Board
considered this relationship in making its affirmative determination that Mr.&nbsp;Bobins
is independent.</font></p>


 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;line-height:10.0pt;margin:12.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">7</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='7',FILE='C:\fc\229162714695_H11179_2359436\19818-1-di.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 17 16:27 2007' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">



<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Executive Sessions<a name="ExecutiveSessions_230840"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Independent
directors of the Board meet in executive session without management as part of
each regular Board meeting and otherwise when circumstances deem it advisable
or necessary. The Chairman of the Nominating and Governance Committee presides
at the executive sessions of independent directors.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Communications
with the Board of Directors<a name="CommunicationsWithTheBoardOfDirec_230841"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Stockholders
and other interested parties may communicate with the Board, the Chairman of
the Board, independent directors as a group, or any individual director or
Committee Chairman by mail addressed to: AAR CORP., Attention: Independent
Directors, or the name of the individual director, c/o Corporate Secretary, AAR
CORP., 1100 N. Wood Dale Road, Wood Dale, Illinois 60191. The independent
members of the Board of Directors have approved procedures for the processing,
review and disposition of all communications sent by stockholders or other
interested parties to the Board of Directors.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Code
of Conduct for the Board of Directors<a name="CodeOfConductForTheBoardOfDirecto_230841"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">All
directors are subject to the Company&#146;s Code of Business Ethics and Conduct. Each
director is furnished a copy of the Code of Business Ethics and Conduct at the
time he becomes a director.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Board Committees<a name="BoardCommittees_230841"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Board has an Audit Committee, a Compensation Committee, a Nominating
and Governance Committee, and an Executive Committee. The following table shows
the committee structure and membership:</font></p>

  <p align="center" style="margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="line-height:1.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Audit
Committee<a name="AuditCommittee_230842"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Audit Committee is comprised entirely of
independent directors qualified to serve on the Audit Committee under
applicable SEC regulations, NYSE rules&nbsp;and the Company&#146;s Categorical
Standards and Policy for Determining Director Independence. Its members are
James E. Goodwin (Chairman), James G. Brocksmith,&nbsp;Jr., Gerald F.
Fitzgerald,&nbsp;Jr., Marc J. Walfish, and Ronald B. Woodard. The Board of
Directors has determined that each member of the Audit Committee is an &#147;audit
committee financial expert,&#148; within the meaning of applicable SEC rules. In
addition, the Board of Directors has determined that service by Mr.&nbsp;Brocksmith
on the Audit Committee of more than three public companies does not impair his
ability to serve effectively on the Company&#146;s Audit Committee.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Audit Committee acts pursuant to a written charter
adopted by the Board of Directors. The charter was last reviewed and approved
by the Audit Committee and the Board of Directors at their July&nbsp;2007
meetings. The full text of the Audit Committee charter appears on the Company&#146;s
web site and is available in print to any stockholder upon written request to
the Secretary of the Company at the Company&#146;s address listed on the first page&nbsp;of
this Proxy Statement.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Audit Committee is
primarily concerned with the integrity of the Company&#146;s financial statements,
compliance with legal and regulatory requirements and the performance of the
Company&#146;s internal </font></p>


 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;line-height:10.0pt;margin:12.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">8</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='8',FILE='C:\fc\229162714695_H11179_2359436\19818-1-di.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 17 16:27 2007' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">



<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">audit function and
independent registered accounting firm. The Audit Committee performs the
specific functions described in its charter and, among other things:</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>approves
and engages the independent registered public accounting firm who audits the
Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>pre-approves
all non-audit/audit related services furnished by the independent registered
public accounting firm;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>maintains
communication between the Board and the independent registered public
accounting firm;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>monitors
the qualifications, independence and performance of the independent registered
public accounting firm;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>oversees
and reviews the Company&#146;s financial reporting processes and practices;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>oversees
and reviews the quality and adequacy of internal controls over financial
reporting, disclosure controls and the organization and performance of the
Company&#146;s internal audit department;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>reviews
the scope and results of audits; and</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>meets
with the independent registered public accounting firm representatives and
internal audit department representative without members of management present.</p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Audit Committee held seven
meetings during Fiscal 2007. The Audit Committee Report for Fiscal 2007 appears
on page&nbsp;42.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Compensation
Committee<a name="CompensationCommittee_230842"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Compensation Committee is
comprised entirely of independent directors as defined under applicable NYSE rules&nbsp;and
the Company&#146;s Categorical Standards and Policy for Determining Director
Independence. Its members are James G. Brocksmith,&nbsp;Jr. (Chairman), Michael
R. Boyce, Ronald R. Fogleman, Patrick J. Kelly, and Ronald B. Woodard.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Compensation Committee acts pursuant to a written charter adopted by the Board
of Directors. The charter was last reviewed by the Compensation Committee and
the Board of Directors at their July&nbsp;2007 meetings. The full text of the
Compensation Committee charter appears on the Company&#146;s web site and is
available in print to any stockholder upon written request to the Secretary of
the Company at the Company&#146;s address listed on the first page&nbsp;of this
Proxy Statement. The Compensation Committee is primarily concerned with
establishing, reviewing and approving Chief Executive Officer compensation,
reviewing and approving other senior executive compensation and overseeing the
Company&#146;s Stock Benefit Plan and any other compensation and employee benefit
plans. The Compensation Committee performs the specific functions described in
its charter and, among other things:</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>reviews and approves compensation policies and practices for all elected
corporate officers, including named executive officers;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>fixes the compensation of the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer and,
together with the full Board, evaluates the Chief Executive Officer&#146;s
performance;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>administers the Company&#146;s annual cash incentive and long-term stock
incentive programs for officers, the AAR CORP. Stock Benefit Plan, and the AAR Section&nbsp;162(m)
Incentive Goal Program;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>recommends director compensation and benefits to the Board for approval;
and</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>oversees administration of certain other employee benefit, director
deferred compensation, savings and retirement plans.</p>


 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;line-height:10.0pt;margin:12.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">9</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='9',FILE='C:\fc\229162714695_H11179_2359436\19818-1-di.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 17 16:27 2007' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">



<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Compensation Committee held three meetings during Fiscal 2007. The Compensation
Committee Report for Fiscal 2007 appears on page&nbsp;17.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Nominating
and Governance Committee<a name="NominatingAndGovernanceCommittee_230843"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Nominating and Governance
Committee is comprised entirely of independent directors as defined under
applicable NYSE rules&nbsp;and the Company&#146;s Categorical Standards and Policy
for Determining Director Independence. Its members are Ronald R. Fogleman
(Chairman), Michael R. Boyce, James E. Goodwin, and Marc J. Walfish.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Nominating and Governance
Committee acts pursuant to a written charter adopted by the Board of Directors.
The charter was last reviewed and approved by the Nominating and Governance
Committee and the Board of Directors at their July&nbsp;2007 meetings. The full
text of the Nominating and Governance Committee charter appears on the Company&#146;s
web site and is available in print to any stockholder upon written request to
the Secretary of the Company at the Company&#146;s address listed on the first
page&nbsp;of this Proxy Statement.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Nominating and Governance Committee is responsible for both nominating and
governance functions as described in its charter. The Nominating and Governance
Committee performs the specific functions described in its charter and, among
other things:</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>oversees the composition, structure and evaluation of the Board and its
committees;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>develops and recommends corporate governance guidelines for Board
approval; and</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>monitors and screens directors for independence and recommends to the
Board qualified candidates for election as directors and to serve on Board
committees.</p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In seeking qualified candidates,
the Nominating and Governance Committee obtains referrals from management,
other directors and business and community leaders, and may retain the services
of a consultant to assist in identifying candidates. The Nominating and
Governance Committee seeks candidates that complement the Board as a whole and
who collectively are strong and diverse in knowledge, skills, experience, and
background. The Committee screens all candidates in the same manner regardless
of the source of the recommendation. When selecting nominees, including those
proposed by stockholders, the Committee looks for candidates who are
independent and have a high level of integrity and professional and personal
ethics and values, as well as demonstrated business acumen, leadership and
policy making experience or special technical skills, irrespective of gender or
ethnicity, as well as other factors the Committee deems appropriate. The
Committee has full discretion in considering its nominations to the Board. The
Company&#146;s Director Nominating Process and Selection Guidelines appear on the
Company&#146;s web site and are available in print to any stockholder upon written
request to the Secretary of the Company at the Company&#146;s address listed on the
first page of this Proxy Statement. The Nominating and Governance Committee
will consider director candidates recommended by stockholders in the same
manner as other candidates. Stockholders may submit a proposed nomination to
the Nominating and Governance Committee for consideration with respect to the
Annual Meeting of Stockholders for the year 2008 by writing to the Secretary,
AAR CORP., One AAR Place, 1100 N. Wood Dale Road, Wood Dale, Illinois 60191. To
be considered, proposed nominations must be received prior to April&nbsp;21,
2008, must state the reasons for the proposed nomination and contain the full
name and address of each proposed nominee, as well as a brief biographical
history setting forth past and present directorships, employment and
occupations, and any other qualifications. Proposed nominations must also
include a statement indicating that the proposed nominees have consented to
being named in the Proxy Statement and to serve if elected.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Nominating and Governance
Committee held two meetings during Fiscal 2007.</font></p>


 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;line-height:10.0pt;margin:12.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">10</font></p>
</div><br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='10',FILE='C:\fc\229162714695_H11179_2359436\19818-1-di.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 17 16:27 2007' -->



<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
<div>


<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Executive Committee<a name="ExecutiveCommittee_224625"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Executive Committee is comprised of David P. Storch (Chairman), James E.
Goodwin, Timothy J. Romenesko and Marc J. Walfish. Mr.&nbsp;Goodwin and Mr.&nbsp;Walfish
are each independent directors as defined by applicable NYSE rules&nbsp;and the
Company&#146;s Categorical Standards and Policy for Determining Director
Independence.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Executive Committee acts pursuant to a written charter adopted by the Board of
Directors. The charter was last reviewed and approved by the Executive
Committee and the Board of Directors at their July&nbsp;2007 meetings. The full
text of the Executive Committee charter appears on the Company&#146;s web site and
is available in print to any stockholder upon written request to the Secretary
of the Company at the Company&#146;s address listed on the first page&nbsp;of this
Proxy Statement.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Executive Committee is authorized to meet between meetings of the Board of
Directors and exercise certain powers of the Board with respect to urgent
matters or other matters referred to it by the Board for deliberation or
action, subject to limitations imposed by the Committee&#146;s charter, the Board,
applicable law and the Company&#146;s By-Laws.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Executive Committee held one meeting during Fiscal 2007.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Directors&#146; Compensation<a name="DirectorsCompensation_224626"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Board believes that compensation for any director who is not an officer or
employee of the Company or any subsidiary (&#147;Non-Employee Director&#148;) should be
primarily a mix of cash and equity compensation. Director compensation and
benefits are recommended to the Board of Directors from time to time by the
Compensation Committee for Board approval.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Currently,
each Non-Employee Director receives an annual retainer of $35,000, a fee of
$2,500 for attendance at each meeting of the Board or of any Board committee
attended in person ($1,250 per meeting for telephonic Board and Committee
meetings), plus reimbursement of expenses. Each committee chairman receives an
additional $5,000 annual retainer. In addition, each Non-Employee Director,
upon being elected a director, receives term life insurance coverage of
$200,000 and is eligible (with spouse) to participate in a Company-paid, annual
physical program. Directors who are officers or employees of the Company or any
subsidiary receive no additional compensation for service on the Board or any
of its committees. The Company also reimburses its directors and, in certain
circumstances, spouses who accompany directors, for travel, lodging and related
expenses they incur in attending Board and Committee meetings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Annual retainer fees are paid
quarterly; Committee Chairman retainer fees are paid annually; meeting fees are
paid promptly following each meeting attended, as are reimbursement of
expenses. Each Non-Employee Director may elect to defer receipt of the annual
retainer and meeting fees pursuant to the Company&#146;s Non-Employee Directors&#146;
Deferred Compensation Plan. Under the Plan, deferred retainer fees are
converted into stock units equivalent to shares of Common Stock, and deferred
meeting fees are credited with interest quarterly based on the 10-year
United States Treasury Bond rate. Distributions of deferred retainer fees under
the plan occur in cash or equivalent value Common Stock, at the participant&#146;s
election, and distribution of deferred meeting fees are made in cash upon termination
of service on the Board and on the happening of certain other events, as
specified in the plan.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>


 <p style="margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">11</font></p>
</div><br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='11',FILE='C:\fc\229194740821_H11179_2359798\19818-1-dk.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 17 19:48 2007' -->



<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
<div>


<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Each
Non-Employee Director also is eligible to receive discretionary stock option
grants and restricted stock awards from time to time under the AAR CORP. Stock
Benefit Plan, as may be determined by the Compensation Committee. Historically,
each Non-Employee Director received an annual stock option grant that expires
ten years from the date of grant and becomes exercisable in 25% increments on
each anniversary grant date at the closing NYSE price on the date of grant. All
unvested stock options became fully vested on May&nbsp;1, 2006. Commencing in
Fiscal 2006, the Compensation Committee determined that, based on a value of
approximately $40,000 per year at the then current stock price, each
Non-Employee Director should receive an annual restricted stock award of 2,500
shares in each of Fiscal Years 2006, 2007, 2008 and 2009 (having a grant date
of July&nbsp;10 of each year), vesting pro rata over a three-year period. Consistent
with the foregoing, each Non-Employee Director received a 2,500 share
restricted stock grant in Fiscal 2007 having a grant date of July&nbsp;10, 2006
and for Fiscal 2008 having a grant date of July&nbsp;10, 2007. Restricted stock
recipients are entitled to receive stock dividends, if any, on restricted stock
grants.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Company terminated the AAR CORP. Non-Employee Directors&#146; Retirement Plan
effective April&nbsp;10, 2001. Any Non-Employee Director who was a
director on the plan&#146;s effective date of termination or a retired director then
receiving benefits under the plan continues to be eligible to receive benefits
pursuant to the terms of the plan as the plan was in effect and applicable to
such participant on the earlier of the date of Plan termination or date of
retirement. Benefits are paid upon reaching age 65 and retirement from the
Board if such director has completed at least five years of service as a
director. Benefits are paid quarterly in cash in an amount equal to 25% of the
annual retainer payable from time to time to an active director and are paid
for a period equal to the total number of years of service as a director to a
maximum of ten years or until death. Continuing liabilities under the plan are
unfunded. As of May&nbsp;31, 2007, six former directors are receiving
retirement benefits under the plan, one former director is eligible to receive
benefits under the plan upon reaching age 65, and one current director, Mr.&nbsp;Brocksmith,
is eligible to receive benefits under the plan upon retirement from the Board.</font></p>


 <p style="margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">12</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='12',FILE='C:\fc\234133319522_D11265_2368459\19818-1-dm.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 22 13:34 2007' -->

following table details the total compensation paid to the Company&#146;s Non-Employee
Directors for Fiscal 2007:</font></p>

in this table as they are employee directors and receive no additional
compensation for their service as directors. Their compensation from the
Company is set forth on the Summary Compensation Table in this Proxy Statement.</font></p>

<p style="line-height:1.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">3</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">The
amounts in this column represent the Company&#146;s expense recognized in Fiscal
2007 for financial statement reporting purposes computed in accordance with FAS
123(R), disregarding any adjustments for potential forfeitures, and thus
includes amounts attributable to awards made in prior years. The grant date
fair value, computed in accordance with FAS 123(R), of restricted stock awarded
to each Non-Employee Director in Fiscal 2007 is $22.68 per share. As of
May&nbsp;31, 2007, the number of restricted shares held by each Non-Employee
Director was as follows: Mr.&nbsp;Boyce 4,167 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Brocksmith 4,167
shares; Mr.&nbsp;Fitzgerald 2,500 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Fogleman 4,167 shares;
Mr.&nbsp;Goodwin 4,167 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Kelly 2,500 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Walfish
4,167 shares; and Mr.&nbsp;Woodard 4,167 shares.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">4</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">The
amounts in this column represent the Company&#146;s expense recognized in Fiscal
2007 for financial statement reporting purposes computed in accordance with FAS
123(R). No stock options were granted to Non-Employee Directors in Fiscal 2007
and all previously issued options held by directors are fully vested. The
aggregate number of shares issuable pursuant to stock options held by each
Non-Employee Director as of May&nbsp;31, 2007 was as follows:&#160; Mr.&nbsp;Boyce, 0;
Mr.&nbsp;Brocksmith,&nbsp;Jr., 17,000; Mr.&nbsp;Fitzgerald,&nbsp;Jr.,0;
Mr.&nbsp;Fogleman, 17,000; Mr.&nbsp;Goodwin, 17,000; Mr.&nbsp;Kelly, 0;
Mr.&nbsp;Walfish, 17,000; and Mr.&nbsp;Woodard, 3,500.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">5</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Mr.&nbsp;Brocksmith
is the only continuing director eligible for a benefit under the Company&#146;s Non-Employee
Directors&#146; Retirement Plan. The amount in this column represents the increase
in the present value of accumulated benefits under the Company&#146;s Non-Employee Directors&#146;
Retirement Plan, as of May&nbsp;31, 2007 determined using assumptions
consistent with those used for reporting purposes in the Company&#146;s 2007
Form&nbsp;10-K. There were no above-market earnings credited under the
Company&#146;s Non-Employee Directors&#146; Deferred Compensation Plan.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">6</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Includes reimbursed expenses in connection with spousal
travel and/or travel and hotel expense in connection with the Company-paid
executive/spouse annual physical program, as well as the cost of the annual
physical program and the cost of term life insurance.</font></p>


 <p style="margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">13</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='13',FILE='C:\fc\234133319522_D11265_2368459\19818-1-dm.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 22 13:34 2007' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">



<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><b><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">V. PROPOSAL 1<br>
</font></b><font size="3" style="font-size:12.0pt;">ELECTION OF
DIRECTORS<a name="V_Proposal1ElectionOfDirectors_042040"></a></font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Board of Directors is presently divided into three classes, each
having three-year terms that expire in successive years. The Board of Directors
has nominated four directors to be elected in Class&nbsp;II at the Annual
Meeting, each to serve a three-year term expiring at the 2010 Annual Meeting or
until the individual is succeeded by another qualified director who has been
duly elected.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The nominees for Director in Class&nbsp;II this
year are Norman R. Bobins, Gerald F. Fitzgerald,&nbsp;Jr., James&nbsp;E.
Goodwin, and Marc J. Walfish.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Information about the nominees and continuing
directors whose terms expire in future years is set forth in Section&nbsp;VI
below.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Each
nominee, except Mr.&nbsp;Bobins, is currently serving as a director of the
Company and each nominee has been determined by the Board to be &#147;independent&#148;
within the meaning of NYSE rules. Mr.&nbsp;Bobins was recommended for
consideration as a director nominee by the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer
of the Company and the Nominating and Governance Committee. He was nominated by
the Board of Directors for election as a Director based on his extensive
business experience, financial and banking expertise and the needs of the
Company. The Board of Directors has determined that Mr.&nbsp;Bobins is
qualified to serve on the Board as an &#147;independent&#148; director within the meaning
of NYSE rules. The Board expects each nominee to serve if elected as a director.
Under Delaware law and the Company&#146;s By-Laws, the nominees for director who
individually receive the greatest number of votes shall be elected directors of
the Company.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:auto;text-align:center;"><b><i><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;font-style:italic;">THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS RECOMMENDS THAT<br>
STOCKHOLDERS VOTE <u>FOR</u> ALL NOMINEES</font></i></b></p>

  <p style="margin:6.0pt 0pt .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  </td>
  <td width="15" valign="top" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:11.6pt;">

 <p style="margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">16</font></p>
