<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
<div>


<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><b><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">VII. EXECUTIVE
COMPENSATION<a name="Vii_ExecutiveCompensation_230124"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;text-transform:uppercase;">Compensation
Committee&#146;s Report On Executive Compensation<a name="CompensationCommitteesReportOnExe_230124"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors
hereby furnishes the following report to the stockholders of the Company in
accordance with applicable SEC rules.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Compensation Committee
states that it has reviewed and discussed the Compensation Discussion and
Analysis with the Company&#146;s management. Based on that review and discussion,
the Compensation Committee recommended to the Board of Directors that the
Compensation Discussion and Analysis be included in this Proxy Statement.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Respectfully submitted,</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">James G. Brocksmith,&nbsp;Jr.,
Chairman<br>
Michael R. Boyce<br>
Ronald R. Fogleman<br>
Patrick J. Kelly<br>
Ronald B. Woodard</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Compensation Discussion
and Analysis<a name="CompensationDiscussionAndAnalysis_230305"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Overview<a name="Overview_230307"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Compensation Committee of the Company&#146;s Board of
Directors is responsible for structuring and administering executive
compensation. The executive compensation program is designed to attract,
motivate and retain talented executives to achieve corporate and business goals
that will result in superior performance and increased stockholder value. The
principal components of the Company&#146;s executive compensation program are annual
base salaries, annual cash incentive opportunities, long-term incentive
opportunities, in the form of stock options and restricted stock awards, and
retirement benefits, each of which is described below. The Company also
provides a limited number of perquisites and other benefits as well as certain
severance and Change in Control benefits, described below.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Compensation Committee is
comprised of five individuals, each of whom (i)&nbsp;has been determined by the
Board of Directors to be an independent director of the Company under
applicable NYSE rules&nbsp;and the Company&#146;s Categorical Standards and Policy
for Determining Director Independence, (ii)&nbsp;is a non-employee director for
purposes of Rule&nbsp;16b-3 of the Exchange Act, and (iii)&nbsp;is an
outside director for purposes of Section&nbsp;162(m)&nbsp;of the Internal
Revenue Code. The Committee relies upon the judgment of its members in making
compensation decisions after reviewing the performance of the Company and
considering an executive&#146;s performance during the year against established
goals, leadership qualities, operational performance, business
responsibilities, career experience, and long-term potential to enhance
shareholder value.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Executive Compensation
Philosophy<a name="ExecutiveCompensationPhilosophy_230314"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The philosophy of the executive compensation program
is to enable the Company to attract, motivate and retain talented executives
capable of achieving strategic business initiatives and producing outstanding
business performance and stockholder value. A principal compensation guideline
of the Committee is that there be a strong link between pay and performance
both at the Company level and the individual level. The types and levels of
performance-based awards are set so that superior performance is rewarded with
superior compensation, while below target performance results in below target
overall compensation. Performance targets for the measures that are tied to
variable compensation are representative of the Company&#146;s expectations of high
performance. As a result, the target total direct compensation for each
executive, defined as the aggregate of base salary, bonus, and long-term
incentives, is intended to be around the third quartile for the comparative
group described below under &#147;Market Comparisons for Setting Compensation
Levels.&#148;</font></p>


 <p style="margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">17</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='17',FILE='C:\fc\227181721925_D11113_2353505\19818-1-do.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 15 18:17 2007' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">



<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Total compensation opportunities for each executive
are intended to be competitive with those offered by other companies competing
for talent in the Company&#146;s employment market. In designing and administering
the individual elements of the executive compensation program for each
executive, the Compensation Committee strives to balance short-term and
long-term incentive objectives and employ prudent judgment in establishing base
salary levels and performance criteria, evaluating performance and determining
actual incentive payments. To ensure competitiveness and reasonableness of the
Compensation Committee&#146;s compensation decisions, compensation consulting firms
are retained periodically to advise the Compensation Committee in connection
with both the design and implementation of the various elements of the program
and the level of individual executive participation. The Company uses
competitive compensation analyses by compensation consultants to establish base
salaries and total compensation opportunities (not actual pay) for the Chairman
of the Board and Chief Executive Officer, the President and Chief Operating
Officer and other executive officers. These compensation opportunities are
established at an appropriate level relative to the third quartile target based
on compensation for such positions at other companies in the relevant
employment market. Generally, as an executive&#146;s level of responsibility
increases, a greater percentage of total compensation opportunity is based on
performance, and the mix of total compensation shifts toward stock, thereby
aligning the long-term interests of senior executives with those of
stockholders.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s Chief Executive
Officer is responsible for bringing recommendations to the Compensation
Committee regarding compensation actions for his direct reports, which include
all of the executive officers named in the Summary Compensation Table. The
Compensation Committee sets the Chief Executive Officer&#146;s compensation. The
Compensation Committee engages an independent consulting firm, Capital H Group,
to assist it in reviewing the Chief Executive Officer&#146;s and certain other executive
officers&#146; compensation, primarily by compiling and analyzing compensation and
performance data of the comparative group of companies described below on a
position-by-position basis.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Market Comparisons for
Setting Compensation Levels<a name="MarketComparisonsForSettingCompen_230318"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company reviews compensation paid by a comparative
group of companies in determining base salary, annual cash incentive
opportunity and long-term incentive opportunity provided to its named executive
officers. The Compensation Committee determined that the appropriate
comparative group of companies for Fiscal 2007, based on the marketplace for
executive talent in the Company&#146;s businesses, were the companies in the S&amp;P
600 Aerospace/Defense smallcap index. The S&amp;P 600 Aerospace/Defense
smallcap index consists of 13 companies, including AAR CORP., Applied Signal
Technology, Armor Holdings,&nbsp;Inc., Ceradyne Inc., Cubic Corp.,
Curtiss-Wright Corp., EDO Corp., Esterline Technologies Corp., GenCorp Inc.,
Kaman Corp., Moog,&nbsp;Inc., Teledyne Technologies Inc., and Triumph Group Inc.
The Committee also reviewed and considered survey information regarding the
compensation practices of similarly-sized non-financial and non-insurance
companies with a</font>nnual revenues of $600 million to $1.5 billion, and
positive return on equity in the past year.</p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In taking compensation
actions, the Compensation Committee also reviews and considers historical compensation
data for named executive officers. This includes rolling 10-year
historical summaries of cash and equity compensation received by executive
officers. When setting compensation levels for Mr.&nbsp;Storch in his
employment agreement entered into on May&nbsp;31, 2006, the Committee reviewed,
and took into consideration, tally sheets prepared by Capital H Group, the
Committee&#146;s compensation consultant, summarizing Mr.&nbsp;Storch&#146;s total annual
compensation, including cash and non-cash direct compensation, cumulative
benefits and savings under retirement plans and equity compensation programs,
perquisites and potential payments on termination of employment, whether on a
Change in Control of the Company or otherwise. The Committee also reviewed and
considered substantially similar total compensation tally sheets when setting
compensation levels for Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko in </font></p>


 <p style="margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">18</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='18',FILE='C:\fc\227181721925_D11113_2353505\19818-1-do.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 15 18:17 2007' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">



<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">connection with his promotion
to President and Chief Operating Officer of the Company on June&nbsp;1, 2007.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Base Salary<a name="BaseSalary_230321"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company provides
competitive base salaries designed to reward individual performance and
contributions consistent with an executive officer&#146;s position and
responsibilities. Base salary levels of all elected corporate officers,
including the Chairman of the Board and Chief Executive Officer, and the other
named executive officers are reviewed annually by the Compensation Committee
and may be adjusted depending upon:</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>the
executive&#146;s current salary;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>the
executive&#146;s qualifications, responsibilities, assessed performance
contribution, including significant changes in responsibility or performance
related to established goals;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>the
executive&#146;s tenure with the Company and the position held by the executive;</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>competitive
salary considerations relative to similar positions at other companies
competing for talent in the Company&#146;s employment market; and</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>the
recommendation of the Chief Executive Officer, in the case of all other executive
officers.</p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Base salaries are generally
set in the second and third quartiles of salary levels of comparable positions
in the cited comparative group of companies. The Company does not target any
specific proportion of total compensation when setting base salary.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Annual Cash Incentive
Opportunities<a name="AnnualIncentiveOpportunities_230536"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Compensation Committee believes that annual
incentive opportunities, payable in cash, serve as an appropriate incentive for
achievement of the Company&#146;s short-term performance goals. Within the first 90
days of each fiscal year, the Company establishes specific performance goals
for its executive officers, including the named executive officers, that govern
the payment of annual cash bonuses for that fiscal year. The Company pays a
cash bonus (not to exceed $5 million in any fiscal year), measured as a
percentage of the executive officer&#146;s salary, based on the extent to which the
Company and the executive achieves applicable performance goals. Performance at
a target level will result in a target bonus, and performance above or below
target generally will result in payment of a bonus at a higher or lower
percentage of salary, respectively. Performance below a minimum threshold will
result in no bonus payment.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For Fiscal 2007, the performance goals for annual cash
incentive opportunities for the named executive officers were based on net
income (target of $40,400,000), return on invested capital (target of 7.5%),
and a leverage ratio (target of 50%), except that the leverage ratio goal
applied only to Mr.&nbsp;Storch, Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko and Mr.&nbsp;Pulsifer. For
purposes of measuring attainment of these performance goals for Fiscal 2007, &#147;net
income&#148; is the Company&#146;s net income reported in its audited financial
statements; return on invested capital means the percentage which results from
dividing net operating profit after tax by the average invested capital; and
leverage ratio is based on maintaining long-term recourse debt-to-capital ratio
of 50% or less. The choice of these performance measures reflects the priority
placed by the Company on preserving and growing stockholder wealth and
maintaining a strong balance sheet. The two performance goals applicable to Mr.&nbsp;Clark
and Mr.&nbsp;McDonald&nbsp;&#151; income and return on invested capital&nbsp;&#151; are
based on the performance of their respective business groups (Aviation Supply
Chain for Mr.&nbsp;Clark and Maintenance, Repair&nbsp;&amp; Overhaul and
Structure and Systems for Mr.&nbsp;McDonald), rather than overall Company
performance.</font></p>


 <p style="margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">19</font></p>
</div><br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='19',FILE='C:\fc\227181721925_D11113_2353505\19818-1-do.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 15 18:17 2007' -->



<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
<div>


<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
relative weight assigned to each of these performance goals for each named executive
officer appears in the table below:</font></p>

<div align="center" style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse;">
 <tr style="page-break-inside:avoid;">

  <p align="left" style="line-height:8.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:left;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Name</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="7" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:5.0pt;">
  <p style="line-height:8.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="202" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:151.65pt;">
  <p style="line-height:8.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="16" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:12.0pt;">
  <p style="line-height:8.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <td width="61" colspan="3" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:45.6pt;">
  <p style="line-height:8.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Net&nbsp;Income</font><font size="1" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">1</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="16" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:12.0pt;">

  </td>
  <td width="78" colspan="3" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:58.85pt;">
  <p style="line-height:8.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Return&nbsp;on<br>

  </td>
  <td width="16" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:12.0pt;">

  <td width="73" colspan="3" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:55.1pt;">
  <p style="line-height:8.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Leverage&nbsp;Ratio</font></p>

<div style="margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><hr size="1" width="64" noshade color="black" align="left" style="width:48.0pt;"></div>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 5.5pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">1</font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">&#160;&#160; Pre-Tax income in the case of Mr. Clark and
Mr. McDonald.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10.5pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The target
annual bonus opportunities as a percentage of base salary for the named
executive officers vary depending on position, the Company&#146;s performance and
the Committee&#146;s individual assessment of their individual contributions, and
are set forth in the table below:</font></p>

<div align="center" style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse;">
 <tr style="page-break-inside:avoid;">
  <td width="31" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:23.0pt;">
  <p align="left" style="line-height:8.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:left;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Name</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="7" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:5.0pt;">
  <p style="line-height:8.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="241" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:180.65pt;">

  </td>
  <td width="20" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:14.7pt;">
  <p style="line-height:12.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:right;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">130</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="22" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:16.7pt;">
  <p style="line-height:12.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">%</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:1.7pt;">
  <p style="line-height:12.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<div style="margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><hr size="1" width="64" noshade color="black" align="left" style="width:48.0pt;"></div>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">1</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Maximum bonus is based upon attainment of
performance goals at 120% of target.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">2</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Mr. Clark&#146;s and Mr.&nbsp;McDonald&#146;s
incentive compensation program operates on a sliding scale. The target
percentage is paid out if their respective business unit meets their respective
specific incentive plan goals. A prorated amount of the target is paid when a
goal is not met but exceeds a sliding threshold. There is no limit on the
incentive payments each can receive under their respective plans, subject to a
maximum of $5 million, since they receive a flat percentage of each dollar that
their respective business unit exceeds the income goal. Under the incentive
compensation programs, the Company reserves the right to reduce the amount
payable based on personal performance and to reflect inclusion or exclusion of
extraordinary items.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Annual cash bonuses granted
for Fiscal 2007 performance to the named executive officers are set forth under
the &#147;Non-Equity Incentive Plan Compensation&#148; column of the Summary Compensation
Table. As shown, Mr.&nbsp;Storch, Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko and Mr.&nbsp;Clark
received actual cash bonuses in excess of their respective target annual cash
incentive opportunities due to performance.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For the fiscal year ending May&nbsp;31,
2008, the Compensation Committee again has set performance goals relating to income,
return on invested capital, and a leverage ratio.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt .5pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Long-term
Incentive Opportunities<a name="LongtermIncentiveOpportunities_231537"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">To reward executives in a
manner that best aligns executives&#146; interests with stockholder interests, the
Company implemented the stockholder-approved AAR CORP. Stock Benefit Plan (&#147;Stock
Benefit Plan&#148;). This long-term incentive program consists of stock options,
performance-based restricted stock awards, employment-based restricted stock
awards, or any combination thereof, granted under the Stock Benefit Plan, in
the discretion of the Compensation Committee. The Stock Benefit Plan also
provides for the use of stock appreciation units; however, to date, no stock
appreciation units have been granted. The specific terms of any restricted
stock or stock option grants are determined by the Compensation Committee prior
to the issuance of grants, subject to the provisions of the Stock Benefit Plan.
The amount of equity incentive compensation granted is based upon the Company&#146;s
strategies and operational and future performance of the Company overall, and
reflects the expected contributions to the Company&#146;s future success.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Generally, when determining
restricted stock and stock option grant opportunities, the Committee considers
the recipient&#146;s position and responsibilities in the Company, performance and
contributions </font></p>


 <p style="margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">20</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='20',FILE='C:\fc\229164314311_H11179_2359436\19818-1-dq.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 17 16:43 2007' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">



<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">made during the preceding
year, capabilities and potential for future contribution to the Company, the
number of restricted stock shares and options previously granted to the
recipient and, for senior management (including the named executive officers),
their stock ownership relative to the Company&#146;s stock ownership guidelines and
the Chief Executive Officer&#146;s recommendation. Under the Company&#146;s stock
ownership guidelines, the Chairman of the Board and Chief Executive Officer is
expected to own Company stock having a value of at least three times his base
salary; the President and Chief Operating Officer and other executive officers
are expected to own stock having a value of at least 75% of their base salary;
and directors are expected to own 10,000 shares of Company stock within four
years of becoming a director.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The current long-term
incentive vehicle for named executive officers is performance-based restricted
stock with grants being issued based on performance over a two-year performance
period, subject to a stock price provision that can accelerate the grant of the
restricted stock award. Actual awards are based on the achievement of goals set
by the Compensation Committee at the beginning of the performance period. For
the two-year performance period beginning June&nbsp;1, 2006 and ending May&nbsp;31,
2008, the Compensation Committee set performance goals based on net income
(target of $54,053,000 in Fiscal 2007 and $62,682,000 in Fiscal 2008) and
return on invested capital (target of 8.0% in Fiscal 2007 and 9.2% in Fiscal
2008), subject to acceleration of the grant of the restricted stock on the 20th
consecutive trading day after the Company&#146;s common stock traded at an average
stock price equal to 30% ($31.30 per share) above its price on the commencement
of the performance period ($24.08 per share). In May&nbsp;2007, the Company&#146;s common
stock reached the targeted price and the Company granted the restricted stock
to the named<b>  </b>executive officers, subject to
the vesting provisions described below. These goals are solely for purposes of
measuring performance under the long-term incentive program and are not
intended to forecast future Company performance.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In connection with Mr.
Romenesko&#146;s promotion to President and Chief Operating Officer, on May&nbsp;30,
2007 the Compensation Committee approved performance restricted stock
opportunities for Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko (15,000 shares) based on performance
against goals for a one-year performance period commencing June&nbsp;1, 2007
and ending on May&nbsp;31, 2008. The Compensation Committee set performance
goals based on net income (target of $67,400,000) and return on invested
capital (target of 9.7%), subject to acceleration of the grant of the
restricted stock on the 20th day after the Company&#146;s common stock trades at a
stock price equal to 30% ($43.47 per share) over its price on the commencement
of the performance period ($33.44 per share). These goals are solely for
purposes of measuring performance under the long-term incentive program and are
not intended to forecast future Company performance.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Once restricted stock awards
are granted based upon satisfaction of the applicable performance goals, or the
common stock price acceleration provision, they are subject to vesting periods
designed to encourage executives to build their careers with the Company. The
restricted stock issued for the two year performance period ending May&nbsp;31,
2008, vests 20% on June&nbsp;1, 2009, 40% on June&nbsp;1, 2011, and 40% on June&nbsp;1,
2013. The award recipient receives dividends, if any, on the restricted shares
and also has the right to vote the restricted shares.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company did not grant any
stock options to its named executive officers in Fiscal 2007 and currently
intends, for the foreseeable future, to rely on grants of performance-based
restricted stock to fund its long-term incentive opportunities for the named
executive officers. Stock option grants, when previously granted, typically
expire ten years from the date of grant or earlier upon termination of
employment, become exercisable at fair market value based on the NYSE closing
stock price on the date of grant in equal increments over a period of three to
five years on successive grant anniversary dates or, in some instances, upon
meeting pre-determined share price performance criteria. Stock option grant
dates are determined by the Compensation Committee and generally are as of the
date of approval by the Compensation Committee, or if the grant is in
connection with a new hire or promotion of an employee, the grant date is the
date of hire or the promotion date, as applicable. </font></p>


 <p style="margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">21</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='21',FILE='C:\fc\229164314311_H11179_2359436\19818-1-dq.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 17 16:43 2007' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">



<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Pursuant to the Company&#146;s
Stock Benefit Plan Internal Administrative Guidelines, the Compensation
Committee may also establish grant dates for options at a specific future date.
All unvested stock options became fully vested on May&nbsp;1, 2006.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt .5pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Retirement
Benefits<a name="RetirementBenefits_231538"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s named
executive officers participate in three retirement plans: the Retirement Plan,
the Retirement Savings Plan and the Supplemental Key Employee Retirement Plan
(the &#147;SKERP&#148;).</font></p>

<p style="font-style:italic;margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Retirement Plan</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Benefit accruals under
the tax-qualified Retirement Plan ceased for all highly compensated employees, including
the named executive officers, on June&nbsp;1, 2005. At termination of
employment, a participant is eligible to receive the amount credited to his
account under the Retirement Plan, which consists of (i)&nbsp;an opening
balance for those participants who participated in the Retirement Plan at December&nbsp;31,
1999 equal to the then present value of the benefit accrued as of such date, (ii)&nbsp;quarterly
pay credits (through May&nbsp;31, 2005 for highly compensated participants)
based on the participant&#146;s age and service, and (iii)&nbsp;quarterly interest
credits until the account is distributed based on the 30-year Treasury
securities rate for the November&nbsp;preceding each such year.</font></p>

<p style="font-style:italic;margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Retirement Savings Plan</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Retirement Savings
Plan is a tax-qualified 401(k)&nbsp;plan that covers most U.S. employees. An
employee can elect to defer up to 75% of his compensation on a pre-tax basis,
up to a maximum of $15,500 in 2007, or $20,500 if age 50 or over. Unless an
employee elects otherwise, participation is automatic at a 3% deferral rate. The
Company provides a matching contribution equal to 20% of the participant&#146;s
deferrals (up to 5% of compensation), a profit sharing contribution of up to 4%
of compensation based on the participant&#146;s deferrals and the performance of the
participant&#146;s operating unit, and a retirement benefit contribution of up to 4%
of compensation based on the participant&#146;s age and service.</font></p>

<p style="font-style:italic;margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">SKERP</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The SKERP is a
nonqualified retirement plan that contains a defined benefit portion and a
defined contribution portion. Benefits accruals ceased as of October&nbsp;1,
2001 for all employees other than Mr.&nbsp;Storch, Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko and Mr.&nbsp;Pulsifer
and were distributed to the participants. The benefits accrued as of May&nbsp;31,
2006 for the three remaining participants have been or will be converted to a
lump sum and transferred by June&nbsp;1, 2008 to the defined contribution
portion of the SKERP. </font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The defined
contribution portion of the SKERP is intended to provide eligible employees
with the portion of their elective deferrals and the Company&#146;s matching and
profit sharing contributions that could not be made under the Retirement
Savings Plan due to Internal Revenue Code limitations on the amount of
compensation that can be taken into account in determining contributions ($225,000
in 2007). The Company also makes annual supplemental contributions equal to 22%
of salary and bonus for Mr.&nbsp;Storch and 10% of salary and bonus for the
other eligible named executive officers.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt .5pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Executive Perquisites<a name="ExecutivePerquisites_231539"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition to the
Company&#146;s Welfare Plans and contractual benefits for executives discussed
elsewhere in this Proxy Statement, it has been the Company&#146;s historical
practice to provide certain other executive perquisites to senior executives.
The Company continues this practice and offers one or more of the following
executive perquisites to named executive officers, depending on the individual
executive&#146;s position, years of service, level of responsibility and total
compensation package:</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Annual vehicle allowance.</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 4.5pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Reimbursement of pre-approved
professional, club and association fees and charges.</p>


 <p style="margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">22</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='22',FILE='C:\fc\229164314311_H11179_2359436\19818-1-dq.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 17 16:43 2007' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">



<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 4.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Reimbursement of travel and
related expenses in connection with participation in meetings of pre-approved
not-for-profit, educational and professional organizations.</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 4.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Third party professional
executive financial planning assistance.</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 4.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Reimbursement of
professional tax preparation fees.</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 4.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Executive and spousal
annual physical and preventative health program.</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 4.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Participation in executive
housing relocation program, including home purchase and reimbursement of
relocation expenses.</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 4.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Executive supplemental
life, split dollar life, long-term disability, accidental death and
dismemberment, and travel insurance.</p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 4.0pt 30.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Symbol" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&#183;</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Reimbursement of travel and
related expenses for spouse traveling with Named Executive Officers.</p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The costs of such
perquisites to the Company are included in the Summary Compensation Table below
in accordance with SEC rules.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Employment, Severance and
Change In Control Agreements<a name="EmploymentSeveranceAndChangeInCon_231540"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company does not
have employment agreements with its executive officers, except for its Chairman
and Chief Executive Officer, David P. Storch. See &#147;Compensation Arrangement
with Chief Executive Officer&#148; on page 26 for a description of the compensation
terms applicable to Mr.&nbsp;Storch under his employment agreement.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company has
severance and Change in Control agreements with each of the named executive
officers other than Mr.&nbsp;Storch. See &#147;Potential Payments Upon Termination
or Change in Control of the Company&#148; on page 37 for a description of these
agreements, including a description of the severance and Change in Control
provisions applicable to Mr.&nbsp;Storch under his employment agreement.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In June, 2007, the
Company adjusted the compensation of Timothy J. Romenesko in connection with
his promotion to President and Chief Operating Officer of the Company,
effective June&nbsp;1, 2007. See footnote 1 to the Summary Compensation Table
on page 24 for a description of the compensation terms applicable to Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko
as President and Chief Operating Officer.</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Impact of Favorable
Accounting/Tax Treatment on Compensation<a name="ImpactOfFavorableAccountingtaxTre_231540"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Federal Income Tax
Considerations<a name="FederalIncomeTaxConsiderations_231540"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 4.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">IRC Section&nbsp;162(m)&nbsp;generally
prevents any public company from claiming a deduction for compensation in
excess of $1 million for the Chief Executive Officer or any of the four highest
compensated executive officers. This deduction limitation, however, does not
apply to performance-based compensation that satisfies certain requirements
under Section&nbsp;162(m). The Compensation Committee has determined that it is
in the best interests of the Company and its stockholders to structure
compensation of executive officers so that compensation will not be subject to
the deduction limit to the extent that it can reasonably do so in a manner that
provides adequate incentives and allows the Company to attract and retain
qualified executives. However, the Compensation Committee has previously and
may in the future structure compensation arrangements that under certain
circumstances may be subject to the deduction limit.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company maintains
the AAR CORP 162(m)&nbsp;Incentive Goal Program. Under this Program, the annual
cash bonuses and performance-based restricted stock awards under the Stock
Benefit Plan qualified in Fiscal 2007 as performance-based compensation under Section&nbsp;162(m).
None of the compensation paid by the Company in Fiscal 2007 was subject to the Section&nbsp;162(m)&nbsp;deduction
limit.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As required under the
tax rules, the Company must obtain stockholder approval every five years of the
material terms of the performance goals for qualifying performance-based
compensation, including annual incentive bonuses. The Company last received
stockholder approval of the performance goals under its 162(m)&nbsp;Incentive
Goal Program at the 2006 annual meeting.</font></p>


 <p style="margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">23</font></p>
</div><br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<div>


<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">SUMMARY COMPENSATION TABLE<a name="SummaryCompensationTable_232740"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table sets forth compensation
information for the Company&#146;s Chief Executive Officer, Chief Financial Officer
and the three other most highly compensated executive officers (&#147;named
executive officers&#148;) for the Fiscal 2007.</font></p>

<div align="center" style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse;">
 <tr style="page-break-inside:avoid;">
  <td width="112" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:83.8pt;">
  <p align="left" style="font-size:8.0pt;line-height:8.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:left;"><!-- SET mrlNoTableShading --><font size="1" style="font-size:6.5pt;">Name and Principal Position</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="7" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:5.0pt;">
  <p style="line-height:8.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.5pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">1</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:7.5pt;">In connection with his promotion to President and Chief
Operating Officer of the Company effective June&nbsp;1, 2007, the Compensation
Committee adjusted Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko&#146;s compensation to reflect his increased
responsibilities. The Compensation Committee established his base salary at
$400,000, increased his target annual cash bonus incentive to 100% of base
salary, and provided him an opportunity to receive 15,000 shares of restricted
stock under the Company&#146;s Stock Benefit Plan based on attainment of performance
goals for the one-year period beginning June&nbsp;1, 2007.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.5pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">2</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:7.5pt;">The amounts in this column represent the Company&#146;s
expense recognized in Fiscal 2007 for financial statement reporting purposes
with respect to all outstanding restricted stock awards held by each named
executive officer, computed in accordance with FAS&nbsp;123(R), disregarding
adjustments for potential forfeitures, and thus includes amounts attributable
to stock awards made in Fiscal 2007 and prior years. See footnote 3 to the
Consolidated Financial Statements contained in the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K
for an explanation of the assumptions made by the Company in the valuation of
these awards. The &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; section of this Proxy
Statement contains additional information about the stock awards made in Fiscal
2007.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.5pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">3</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:7.5pt;">No stock options were granted to any named executive
officer in Fiscal 2007 and all outstanding options held by the named executive
officers have vested. Accordingly, the Company recognized no expense in Fiscal
2007 for financial statement reporting purposes with respect to stock options
held by the named executive officers.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.5pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">4</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:7.5pt;">This column shows the annual cash incentives earned by
each named executive officer for Fiscal 2007 under the Company&#146;s bonus plan
covering named executive officers. The &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148;
section of this Proxy Statement contains additional information about the
incentive compensation.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.5pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">5</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:7.5pt;">This column includes amounts transferred from the defined
benefit portion of the SKERP to the defined contribution portion of the SKERP
for Messrs. Storch, Romenesko and Pulsifer. There were no above-market earnings
credited under the Company&#146;s Non-Employee Directors&#146; Deferred Compensation Plan.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.5pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">6</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:7.5pt;">All other compensation received by each
named executive officer in Fiscal 2007 is as follows: </font></p>

<p style="line-height:1.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;line-height:9.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:7.5pt;">*</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:7.5pt;">In connection with the cessation of
benefit accruals (as described above) under the Retirement Plan, effective June&nbsp;1,
2005, supplemental payments are made on a periodic basis directly to highly
compensated employees who were previously receiving grandfathered or transition
benefits under the Retirement Plan. This additional benefit is based on a
formula that provides for a continuation of grandfathered and transition
benefits as previously provided under the Retirement Plan, offset by the value
of the retirement benefit contribution (described above) provided under the
Retirement Savings Plan.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;line-height:9.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.5pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">7</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:7.5pt;">Mr.&nbsp;McDonald resigned as an officer
of the Company effective May&nbsp;31, 2007 and as an employee effective July&nbsp;31,
2007.</font></p>


 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;line-height:10.0pt;margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">25</font></p>
</div><br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='25',FILE='C:\fc\22917026179_H11179_2359436\19818-1-ds.htm',USER='jmsproofassembler',CD='Aug 17 17:01 2007' -->



<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
<div>


<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Compensation
Arrangement with Chief Executive Officer<a name="CompensationArrangementWithChiefE_235727"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company has an employment
agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Storch that was amended and restated for a term
commencing May&nbsp;31, 2006 and ending May&nbsp;31, 2010 subject to extension
by the parties. The agreement provides for (i)&nbsp;a base salary of not less
than $717,100 per year or such increased amount as the Compensation Committee
may determine, (ii)&nbsp;an annual cash incentive opportunity of up to 150% of
Base Salary for performance against financial goals established by the
Compensation Committee; (iii)&nbsp;a long-term equity incentive compensation
opportunity to receive shares of restricted stock under the Company&#146;s Stock
Benefit Plan as described in the next paragraph below; (iv)&nbsp;specified
fringe benefits, including personal use for Mr.&nbsp;Storch and his
accompanying family members of Company aircraft (subject to payment by Mr.&nbsp;Storch
for each accompanying passenger), annual automobile allowance, payment of
country club dues, fees and certain charges, reimbursement of dues, fees,
charges and expenses relating to membership in professional clubs/organizations
and not-for-profit educational organizations, financial planning and tax
preparation services, executive physical, and payment of reasonable legal fees
incurred to negotiate the agreement.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Under his long-term incentive
opportunity, Mr.&nbsp;Storch can receive restricted stock based on two two-year
performance periods, from June&nbsp;1, 2006 through May&nbsp;31, 2008 and from June&nbsp;1,
2008 through May&nbsp;31, 2010. The value of Mr.&nbsp;Storch&#146;s long-term equity
incentive compensation opportunity is equal to $600,000 for achievement of each
of the following performance goals: (a)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s net income for each
fiscal year within a performance period and (b)&nbsp;return on invested capital
for each fiscal year within a performance period, plus an additional award
opportunity of up to 50% of the total two-year award, based on the combined
achievement against these two goals for each performance period, for an
aggregate opportunity value of up to $3.6 million for each two-year performance
period. The number of shares available to be granted with respect to each
fiscal year within the performance period will be determined at the beginning
of each such performance period by dividing $600,000 by the fair market value
of one share of Common Stock on that date, based on the NYSE closing price for
such date. If at any time during the performance period, the closing price of
Common Stock is 50% higher than the price at the beginning of the performance
period for 20 consecutive trading days, all performance restricted stock
opportunity shares (including the additional 50% opportunity) will be granted
immediately.</font></p>


 <p style="line-height:10.0pt;margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">26</font></p>
</div><br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

awards made in Fiscal 2007, and (4)&nbsp;stock options granted in Fiscal 2007.</font></p>

  <p style="margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <td width="6" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:4.8pt;">

  <td width="17" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:13.0pt;">

</div>

<p style="line-height:1.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><hr size="1" width="64" noshade color="black" align="left" style="width:48.0pt;"></div>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">1</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:6.0pt;">The grant date of restricted stock awards is the date
the stock price performance target was achieved.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">2</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:6.0pt;">On the date the Compensation Committee established the
performance periods, and approved the performance goals, for the restricted
stock awards, it also authorized the grant of restricted stock with a grant
date of the earlier of the last day of the performance period or the date
during each performance period when the Company&#146;s average stock price is 30%
higher than the price at the beginning of each performance period for 20
consecutive trading days.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">3</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:6.0pt;">Payouts under the Company&#146;s bonus plan covering named
executive officers were based on performance for Fiscal 2007, which has now
occurred. Thus, the information in these columns reflect the range of potential
payouts when the performance goals were set in July&nbsp;2006. The amounts
actually paid under the plan for Fiscal 2007 appear in the &#147;Non-Equity Incentive
Plan Compensation&#148; column of the Summary Compensation Table. See the &#147;Compensation
Discussion and Analysis&#148; section of this Proxy Statement for a description of
the bonus plan, including the performance goals.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">4</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:6.0pt;">The information in these columns show the range of
potential restricted stock grants that could have been earned by the named
executive officers based on the two year performance period beginning June&nbsp;1,
2006. The restricted stock was granted on May&nbsp;11, 2007, which was the date
during the performance period when the Company&#146;s stock price was 30% higher
than the price at the beginning of the performance period for 20 consecutive
trading days. The actual number of shares of restricted stock awarded for the
performance period is as follows:&#160; Mr.&nbsp;Storch,
130,000; Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko, 30,000; Mr.&nbsp;Clark, 30,000; Mr.&nbsp;McDonald,
30,000; Mr.&nbsp;Pulsifer, 30,000.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">5</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:6.0pt;">No stock options were granted to any named executive
officer in Fiscal 2007.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">6</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:6.0pt;">The column shows the grant date fair value, computed in
accordance with FAS 123(R), of the restricted stock awarded to each named
executive officer in Fiscal 2007.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><i><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.0pt;font-style:italic;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">7</font></i><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:4.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:6.0pt;">Mr.&nbsp;Clark&#146;s
and Mr.&nbsp;McDonald&#146;s Incentive Compensation Program operates on a sliding scale.
The target percentage is paid out if their respective business unit meets their
specific incentive plan goals exactly. A prorated amount of the target is paid
when a goal is not met but exceeds a sliding threshold. There is no limit on
the incentive payments each can receive since they receive a flat percentage of
each dollar that their respective business unit exceeds the income goal.</font></p>


 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;line-height:10.0pt;margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">27</font></p>
</div><br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

award of restricted stock that was not vested and remained outstanding as of May&nbsp;31,

<div style="margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><hr size="1" width="64" noshade color="black" align="left" style="width:48.0pt;"></div>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 20.0pt;text-indent:-20.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">1</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">All stock options held by named executive
officers are fully vested. Certain options listed are &#147;reload&#148; options which
have an exercise price equal to the NYSE closing price on the date the original
option was exercised but retain the original option expiration date. The
Company no longer grants reload options and all outstanding options have been
amended to eliminate the reload provisions.</font></p>


 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">29</font></p> <br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<p style="line-height:1.0pt;margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 20.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Vesting is accelerated upon the participant&#146;s
termination of employment as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 20.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Retirement (as defined in the Stock Benefit Plan): For
the 10/8/97, 7/11/00 and 7/21/03 awards, the awards vest as of such retirement
date. For the 5/31/05, 6/3/05 and 5/11/07 awards, the awards vest in accordance
with the vesting schedule.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 20.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">Death or Disability (as
defined in the Stock Benefit Plan) on or before third anniversary of
grant:&#160; the difference between one-half
of the total award shares and the number of shares already vested will vest as
of such termination. After the third anniversary of grant:&#160; all award shares vest as of such termination.</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 20.0pt;text-indent:-20.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">3</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">This column shows the market value of the
unvested restricted stock held by the named executive officers, based on a
price of $32.50 per share (the closing market price of the common stock on May&nbsp;31,
2007).</font></p>

<p style="font-family:Times New Roman;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 20.0pt;text-indent:-20.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">4</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">All restricted stock for Mr.&nbsp;McDonald
not vested on July&nbsp;31, 2007 was forfeited pursuant to the terms of the
restricted stock grant due to his resignation.</font></p>


 <p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font face="Times New Roman">30</font></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:center;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Option Exercises and
Stock Vested<a name="OptionExercisesAndStockVested_235308"></a> Table</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">This table
sets forth information for each named executive officer concerning (1)&nbsp;the
exercise of options during Fiscal 2007, (2)&nbsp;the dollar amount realized on
exercise of the options, (3)&nbsp;the number of shares of restricted stock that
vested during Fiscal 2007, and (4)&nbsp;the value of those vested shares.</font></p>

<div style="margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><hr size="1" width="64" noshade color="black" align="left" style="width:48.0pt;"></div>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">1</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">These amounts represent the pre-tax difference between
the option exercise price and the closing market price of the common stock on
the date of exercise, multiplied by the number of shares of common stock
covered by the options exercised.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6.0pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:5.0pt;position:relative;top:-2.0pt;">2</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font size="1" style="font-size:8.0pt;">These amounts represent the closing market price of the
common stock on the date of vesting, multiplied by the number of shares that
vested.</font></p>


 <p style="line-height:10.0pt;margin:24.0pt 0pt .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">31</font></p>
</div><br><hr size="3" width="100%" noshade color="#010101" align="center">

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
<div>


<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:11.0pt;">Retirement
Program Benefits</font></b><a name="RetirementProgramBenefits_235346"></a></p>

<p style="font-weight:bold;margin:0pt 0pt 2.0pt 10.0pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Pension Benefits<a name="PensionBenefits_235346"></a></font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company provides defined
benefit pension benefits under the Supplemental Key Employee Retirement Plan (&#147;SKERP&#148;)
and the Retirement Plan. This table shows the years of service currently
credited to each named executive officer under the applicable plan and the
present value of the accumulated benefit payable under the applicable plan to
each named executive officer at the earliest age an unreduced benefit is
payable.</font></p>

  <p style="margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="78" valign="bottom" style="padding:0pt .7pt 0pt 0pt;width:58.25pt;">
  <p align="left" style="margin:0pt 0pt .0001pt;page-break-after:avoid;text-align:left;"><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;">SKERP</font></p>
